GRADE 10 PHYSICS EXPERIMENTS
PHY-G10-001

Title: Measuring Length Using Vernier Calipers and Micrometer Screw Gauge
Subject Area: General Physics
Topic: Measurement
Objective: Measure length/diameter accurately using precision instruments.
Apparatus: Vernier calipers, micrometer screw gauge, ruler, objects
Procedure Summary: Measure dimensions of objects using each tool and compare accuracy.
Expected Outcome: Learners understand precision measurement and error differences.
Simulation Type: Interactive Measurement Tool
Difficulty: Beginner

PHY-G10-002

Title: Determining the Period of a Simple Pendulum
Subject Area: Mechanics
Topic: Time and Motion
Objective: Investigate factors affecting pendulum period.
Apparatus: String, bob, stopwatch, retort stand
Procedure Summary: Vary string length and measure oscillation time.
Expected Outcome: Period depends on length, not mass.
Simulation Type: Pendulum Motion Simulation
Difficulty: Beginner

PHY-G10-003

Title: Measuring Mass and Weight
Subject Area: General Physics
Topic: Mass and Weight
Objective: Distinguish between mass and weight practically.
Apparatus: Beam balance, spring balance
Procedure Summary: Measure same object using both balances.
Expected Outcome: Mass constant, weight depends on gravity.
Simulation Type: Digital Lab Instrument
Difficulty: Beginner

PHY-G10-004

Title: Locating the Centre of Mass of an Irregular Lamina
Subject Area: Mechanics
Topic: Equilibrium
Objective: Determine centre of gravity of irregular shapes.
Apparatus: Cardboard lamina, pin, plumb line
Procedure Summary: Suspend lamina from different points and mark lines.
Expected Outcome: Intersection gives centre of mass.
Simulation Type: Virtual Balance Simulation
Difficulty: Intermediate

PHY-G10-005

Title: Verification of Hooke’s Law
Subject Area: Forces
Topic: Elasticity
Objective: Investigate extension proportional to force.
Apparatus: Spring, weights, ruler
Procedure Summary: Add weights progressively and record extension.
Expected Outcome: Linear graph confirms Hooke’s Law.
Simulation Type: Spring Extension Simulation
Difficulty: Intermediate

PHY-G10-006

Title: Investigating Friction on Different Surfaces
Subject Area: Forces
Topic: Friction
Objective: Compare frictional forces on surfaces.
Apparatus: Wooden block, spring balance, rough/smooth surfaces
Procedure Summary: Pull block across surfaces and compare force.
Expected Outcome: Rougher surfaces produce greater friction.
Simulation Type: Friction Force Simulation
Difficulty: Beginner

PHY-G10-007

Title: Principle of Moments Using a Metre Rule
Subject Area: Moments
Topic: Turning Effect of Forces
Objective: Verify clockwise moment = anticlockwise moment.
Apparatus: Metre rule, pivot, weights
Procedure Summary: Balance weights at different distances.
Expected Outcome: Principle of moments verified.
Simulation Type: Lever Balance Simulation
Difficulty: Intermediate

PHY-G10-008

Title: Work Done and Power Calculation
Subject Area: Energy
Topic: Work, Energy, Power
Objective: Determine work done and power output.
Apparatus: Weights, stopwatch, height scale
Procedure Summary: Lift object through height and time it.
Expected Outcome: Practical understanding of work and power formulas.
Simulation Type: Energy Calculator
Difficulty: Beginner

PHY-G10-009

Title: Mechanical Advantage of Simple Machines
Subject Area: Machines
Topic: Levers and Pulleys
Objective: Calculate MA, VR, and efficiency.
Apparatus: Pulley system, lever, weights
Procedure Summary: Compare load and effort.
Expected Outcome: Efficiency less than 100% due to losses.
Simulation Type: Machine Efficiency Simulation
Difficulty: Intermediate

